findings.suggestion:
Add a catch block that logs the error with job context (id, name, handler) and emits it through an onError callback or event. Track failed runs separately from successful ones (e.g., a lastError field or separate errorCount). Example:

try {
  await handler(currentRecord)
  this.store.updateLastRun(record.id, new Date().toISOString(), currentRecord.runCount + 1)
} catch (err) {
  this.onError?.(new Error(`Job ${record.id} (${record.name}) handler '${record.handler}' failed`, { cause: err }))
}

Throw an error when the handler is not registered, BEFORE saving to the store. Validate handler registration upfront:

const handler = this.handlers.get(options.handler)
if (!handler) {
  throw new Error(`Handler '${options.handler}' not registered. Register it with registerHandler() before scheduling jobs.`)
}

Alternatively, move store.save() after scheduleJob() succeeds, so failed scheduling does not leave orphaned records.

