findings.suggestion:
Wrap the finally block's DB operation in its own try/catch:

finally {
  try {
    this.store.updateLastRun(record.id, new Date().toISOString(), currentRecord.runCount + 1)
  } catch (dbErr) {
    this.onError?.(new Error(`Failed to update run metadata for job ${record.id}`, { cause: dbErr }))
  }
}

Wrap the Cron constructor in try/catch. Either remove the orphaned record on failure, or validate inputs before saving:

try {
  // ... new Cron(...)
} catch (err) {
  this.store.remove(record.id)
  throw new Error(`Failed to schedule job '${record.name}' (${record.mode}: ${record.schedule})`, { cause: err })
}

findings.code_snippet:
start(): void {
  const jobs = this.store.list()
  for (const job of jobs) {
    if (!job.enabled)
      continue
    if (job.mode === 'at' && new Date(job.schedule) <= new Date())
      continue
    this.scheduleJob(job)
  }
}

findings.suggestion:
Wrap each scheduleJob call in try/catch to isolate per-job failures:

for (const job of jobs) {
  if (!job.enabled) continue
  if (job.mode === 'at' && new Date(job.schedule) <= new Date()) continue
  try {
    this.scheduleJob(job)
  } catch (err) {
    this.onError?.(new Error(`Failed to schedule job '${job.name}' (${job.id})`, { cause: err }))
  }
}

Use try/finally to ensure the store is always closed:

close(): void {
  try {
    this.stop()
  } finally {
    this.store.close()
  }
}

Add a closed flag and guard at the top of each public method:

private closed = false

